{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:57:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:57:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2673"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2673"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.25,0.12,0.17,0.03,0.44]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59861"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2673"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45278"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1558"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17689"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59861"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of worsening nausea. He has also experienced one episode of vomiting, increasing urination and thirst, and fatigue. He has no fever, chest or abdominal pain, constipation, or diarrhoea. He has a medical history of ST-elevation myocardial infarction two years ago, where a stent was placed in his left anterior descending artery. He was also recently diagnosed with stage IV non-small cell lung cancer. His medications include aspirin, ticagrelor, and metoprolol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears lethargic. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. There is reduced skin turgor and tender muscles. Laboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 98 g/L (130-170)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 8.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelets: 245 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003ESodium: 145 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 4.9 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003ECreatinine: 160 \u00b5mol/L (60-110)\u003Cbr /\u003EeGFR: 35 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90)\u003Cbr /\u003ECorrected calcium: 3.2 mmol/L (2.1-2.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn intravenous line is inserted and an ECG is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be found on ECG?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Long QT interval","Flat T waves","Hyperacute T waves","ST-elevation in leads II, III and aVF","Short QT interval"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia, confirmed by his corrected calcium of 3.2 mmol/L. The symptoms of polyuria, polydipsia, nausea, and fatigue are typical. On ECG, hypercalcaemia characteristically causes a \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort QT\u003C/strong\u003E interval due to acceleration of phase 2 and 3 of the cardiac action potential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELong QT\u003C/strong\u003E interval is seen in hypocalcaemia, which typically presents with tetany, paraesthesias, and Chvostek\u0027s sign - none of which are present here. The calcium level clearly shows this is not the case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperacute T waves\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of hyperkalaemia or acute myocardial ischaemia. This patient\u0027s potassium is normal at 4.2 mmol/L, and he has no chest pain to suggest acute coronary syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlat T waves\u003C/strong\u003E are typically seen in hypokalaemia, which is not present here given the normal potassium level. While T wave flattening can occasionally occur in severe hypercalcaemia, QT shortening is a more consistent and earlier finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EST-elevation in leads II, III, and aVF\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate an inferior wall myocardial infarction. While this patient has a history of coronary artery disease, he has no chest pain or other symptoms to suggest acute ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this patient would include urgent intravenous fluids and consideration of bisphosphonates given the severity of hypercalcaemia (\u0026gt;3.0 mmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypercalcaemia can cause a shortening of the QT interval on ECG.","Malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia commonly presents with polyuria, polydipsia, nausea, and fatigue.","A corrected calcium above 3.0 mmol/L requires urgent treatment."],"references":["Chorin E, Rosso R, Viskin S. Electrocardiographic Manifestations of Calcium Abnormalities. Ann Noninvasive Electrocardiol. 2016 Jan;21(1):7-9. doi: 10.1111/anec.12316. Epub 2015 Nov 2. PMID: 26524386; PMCID: PMC6931435."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45278"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2673"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45278"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-09T11:25:35+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-09T11:26:27+10:30"},"relationships":